I will take the position that it is morally wrong to prolong pain, anguish and human suffering. I've given this a lot of thought obviously, with my med termination history. <br>
<br>
Seems to me the only way one can justisfy allowing another human to suffer needlessly (that is, suffer when there is no hope of recovery, only impending death) is to bring god into it and say &quot;it's up to god&quot; or &quot;god wants them/us to learn something&quot; or &quot;we have to give god a chance to make a miracle&quot; or in the case of a severely compromised fetus &quot;god is sending them here to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>do</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> something.&quot; Take god out of the equation and there really is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>no justification</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for allowing needless human suffering.<br>
<br>
That said, I will add that there is certainly a slipperly slope to be concerned with where euthanasia is allowed. Who determines whether a person is truly being relieved of suffering or whether it is their caretakers who are being relieved of the burden of their care? That is a toughie.<br>
<br>
From my memory (especially as a Michigan resident) it seems that in all cases Dr. Jack Kervorkian used the utmost care in determining that his patients truly wanted to die.<br>
<br>
I also remember when my friend's mom died of cancer, she was in so much pain and she was angry that they wouldn't just let her die. She said &quot;it is so unfair that prisoners on death row can die but I am sentenced to live with this pain.&quot; It was awful. Even her mouth was filled with chanker sores.<br>
<br>
Another memory is my grandma dying of conjestive heart failure, in the hospital for the upteenth time, intubated, unable to talk and writing a note to me that said &quot;Christ on the cross had NOTHING on this!<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> &quot;<br>
<br>
